quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
  46,21,"And recall the brother of ʻĀd{1}when he warned his people at the dunes—and warnings had passed away before him and after him: “Worship none but Allah; I fear for you<sup>pl </sup>the punishment of a great day.”",1:[Prophet Hûd who was sent to the people of ʻĀd.]
  46,22,"They said, “Have you<sup>sg </sup>come to us to divert us from our gods? Then bring us what you promise us, if you are of the truthful.”"
  46,23,"He said, “Indeed, all knowledge is only with Allah, and I proclaim{1}to youwhat I have been sent with, but I see you are an ignorant people.”",1:[Qira’at: Abu Amr read it as: “…and I compile and proclaim to you…”]
  46,24,"Then, when they saw it as a cloud approaching their valleys, they said, “This is a cloud that will bring us rain.” “Rather, it is what you<sup>pl </sup>sought to hasten: a wind in which is painful punishment,"
  46,25,"destroying everything by the command of its Lord.” And when the morning came upon them, nothing could be seen{1}except their residences. Thus We repay the criminal people.",1:[Qira’at: All except for Asem, Hamza, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “… you<sup><small>sg</small></sup> could see nothing except…”]
  46,26,"And surely We had empowered them in the same way as We empowered you<sup>pl </sup>and We gave them hearing, and sight<i>(s) </i>{1}, and burning hearts. But neither their hearing, nor their sight<i>(s) </i>, nor their burning hearts availed them in any way. That is because they used to repudiate the signs{2}of Allah, and so they became surrounded by what they used to ridicule.",1:[Mentioned in plural form in Arabic, denoted by (s) in English for grammatical reasons.],2:[The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.]
  46,27,"And most surely We have annihilated many towns around you<sup>pl </sup>and diversified the signs, that they may return<i>(to the truth) </i>."
  46,28,"Why then did those whom they worshiped as means of nearness to Allah not support them? Rather, they abandoned{1}them. It was their lie, a fabrication of their own making.",1:[Literally “…they strayed from them.”]
